Hyper Parameter combinations

Different hyper parameters of SOM Brero model were considered with respect to FS1 and FS2 data.

Map Size :

  • Larger map sizes result in more detailed patterns; smaller map sizes result in more general patterns

Two radius types are allowed in SOMBrero package.

Various distance types are allowed.

Prototype for the SOM can be initialized randomly, pca: prototypes are initialized to the observations closest to a grid along the two first principal components of the data

scaling : Unitvar and center is used. Unitvar is for numeric data which is centered and scaled. Center is Korrespe was not used as it is only applicable for the contigency tables where the frequency distribution of the variables is displayed.

#--------------------------------------------------------#

k_max = floor(N^(2/5))# floor(N^(1/2))

p_max= 0.15* N

#shape of SOM.. depends on the Pmin and 
r_min= ceiling(P_min^(1/2))
r_max= max(r_min+5,floor(p_max ^(1/2)))

Partial dependence

Need for pdp : Quantifying predictor importance.

Partial dependence plots are used for displying marginal dependency of predictors on the target variable. Different packages can be used for analysing partial dependency such as pdp, iceplots. Even some learning models like random forest and gradient booting regressor have built in method to highlight the partial dependencies. PDPs visualizes the relationship between a subset of the features (max 3) and the target variable while considering the average effect of the other predictors in the model.

Analysis of impact of hyper parameters on QE

In my thesis, PDPs will help to interpret the marginal dependency of different hyper parameters on either Quantization Error or Topographic Error ( i.e.QE or TE namely).

Quantization Error

  • The QE is the average distance between each data vector and the BMU.
  • The quantization error calculates the mean squared euclidean distance between the sample vectors and their respective cluster prototypes.
  • which helps quantify the quality of the clustering
  • declines as the map becomes larger.
  • Larger map sizes result in more detailed patterns; smaller map sizes result in more general patterns.
  • Quantization Error can not be used to com-pare maps of diffe rent sizes. [Show pdp for one dimension]

Conclusion on QE (TE was not considered during this analysis)

  • QE was significantly low with below features dimension: higher dimension..14 Radius type : Letremy Init proto : pca and obs Max itr: more than 4000 Scaling : both center and unitvar had similar effect as per our data eps_0 : shows similar result for all the values more than 0.3

Topographic Error

  • is the topology preservation measure
  • For all data samples, the respective best and second-best matching units are identified
  • If these are not adjacent on the map lattice, this is considered an error.
  • TE is calculated as the ratio of sample vectors for which the second best matching unit is not in the direct neighborhood of the best matching unit.
  • TE is always normalized in the range [0,1]
  • 0 means topology is perserved perfectly
  • Topographic Error is not reliable for small maps.
  • TE provides an insight on the good organization on the map

Conclusion for TE ( QE was not considered during analysis)

  • TE was significantly low with below features dimension: throughout dimension had no impact.. only below mentioned featured had impact Radius type : gaussian Init proto : all three same Max itr: initially slightly high but then throught same Scaling : both center and unitvar had similar effect as per our data eps_0 : shows similar result for all the values more than 0.3
